= Marxist Parties [+ leftist_parties +]%

Marxist Parties see an intrisic connection between production and society, and seek the construction of a classless, equal society based on the theories of Karl Marx. Marxist forces in Germany have generally offered principled opposition to the Syndicalist movement, either criticizing its bureaucracy, inefficiency, or nationalist tendencies, aligning themselves closer with traditional Marxist movements.

With the Liegnitz programme and the return of the USPD into the party, the SPD has affirmed itself as a Marxist Party and became the de facto face of Marxism in Germany. However, this has came with some consequences: .

{!<table>!} 
{!<tr><td>Party</td><td>Vote share</td><td>% Change</td><td> Seats</td><td> Seat Change</td></tr>!}
{!<tr><td><div class="box" style='background-color:#E3000F; outline: 2px; outline-style: solid;'> </div> !} **SPD:** {!</td><td>!} **[+ spd_r +]%** {!</td><td>!} **[+ str_change_spd +]%** {!</td><td>!} [+ spd_seats +] {!</td><td>!} [+ spd_seats_change_display +] {!</td></tr>!}
{!<tr><td><div class="box" style='background-color:#D10000'> </div> !} SP: {!</td><td>!} [+ sp_r +]% {!</td><td>!} [+ str_change_sp +]% {!</td><td>!} [+ sp_seats +] {!</td><td>!} [+ sp_seats_change_display +] {!</td></tr>!}
{!</table>!}

= Catholic Parties [+ catholic_parties +]%

Catholicism has became a very strong political force in Germany, with Zentrum positioning itself as a party of the Catholics, who overwhelmingly vote for it. Catholics primarily desire the protection of religions and traditions in German society, but are much more amenable to material conditions or government intervention than Liberals or Conservatives.

A number of regionalist parties such as the BVP or the LRP have aligned themselves with Zentrum, these parties have turned their home locations into strongholds, though they tend to be a lot more conservative than Zentrum, who sees significant influence from left-wing Catholics and progressives.

